# Access & scopes for tracking `{{REPO_SLUG}}` on GitHub

This is the bulletproof checklist for giving the tracker (and `seed-github.sh`) enough access to project this project's roadmap onto GitHub. Read it before the first sync, because the most common failure — Projects living at org scope, not repo scope — is invisible until a step silently can't run. The rule the script follows is: confirm access first, and on any gap print exactly what is missing and how to grant it, then **downgrade a tier** rather than abort. Nothing here is destructive; granting more access only unlocks more of the chain (issues -> issues+Project -> wiki).

## Repo settings (do these in the `{{REPO_SLUG}}` UI)

Enable **Issues** under Settings -> Features, because without it no issue or milestone can be created and the tracker drops straight to the paste-able Tier-C list. <!-- IF:WIKI -->Enable the **Wiki** under Settings -> Features **and create its first page in the browser** before any `git push`, because `<repo>.wiki.git` does not exist as a pushable repo until that first page initializes it.<!-- /IF --> For CI automation, set Settings -> Actions -> General -> Workflow permissions to **Read and write** and tick **Allow GitHub Actions to create and approve pull requests**, so a workflow-driven sync can open issues and PRs.

## `gh` CLI scopes (the simplest path)

Authenticate once, then add the Projects scope, because a fresh `gh auth login` does not include it and the Project steps will be skipped without it:

```bash
gh auth login
gh auth refresh -s project,read:project,repo
gh auth status   # verify: the line "Token scopes:" should list project, read:project, repo
```

A `repo`-scoped classic token created through `gh` can also push the wiki, which matters because not every token type can (see below).

## The Projects-v2 gotcha (most common failure)

Projects v2 live at **organization or user scope, not repository scope**. That single fact is why a token that can create issues all day still cannot touch a board. Whatever credential you use, the Project steps need an explicit org/user Projects grant on top of repo access; when it is absent the script notices it during preflight, prints the fix, and continues at the issues-only tier.

## Choosing a credential

Pick the credential that matches how the sync runs — locally by a person, or in CI:

- **Classic PAT** — needs `repo` (covers issues and wiki) **plus `project`** for Projects, and add `workflow` if it must edit files under `.github/workflows/`. A classic PAT *can* push the wiki.
- **Fine-grained PAT** — needs repository permissions **Issues: Read and write**, **Contents: Read and write**, **Pull requests: Read and write**, and **Metadata: Read**, **plus the organization permission "Projects: Read and write"** for org Projects. Note the sharp edge: **fine-grained PATs cannot push wikis** — use a classic PAT or your `gh` credentials for wiki edits.
- **GitHub App** — needs **Issues / Contents / Pull requests: Read and write** and **Organization Projects: Read and write**, installed on `{{REPO_SLUG}}` (or its org). Best for shared automation that should not be tied to one person.

## Running the sync inside GitHub Actions

The Actions default token can open issues and PRs when the workflow declares a `permissions:` block, but it **cannot modify org Projects v2 and cannot push the wiki**. For those steps, store a classic PAT or GitHub App token as the `PROJECTS_TOKEN` repository secret (Settings -> Secrets and variables -> Actions) and pass it to the relevant step's environment using the standard `secrets.` Actions reference — written in the workflow's `env:` as a reference to that secret, not inlined here, so this document is never mistaken for an unfilled template token. Use the default token for issue/PR steps and `PROJECTS_TOKEN` only for the Project/wiki steps.

## Preflight you can run now

Run this before the first sync; it is the same shape the script runs, and it tells you which tier you will land at:

```bash
gh auth status                                                   # is the 'project' scope present?
gh repo view {{REPO_SLUG}} --json hasIssuesEnabled,hasWikiEnabled # are the features on?
gh project list --owner "$(echo {{REPO_SLUG}} | cut -d/ -f1)"     # can you see/create Projects?
```

If any line fails, the message above tells you the exact grant to add. Re-run after granting; the sync is idempotent, so re-running never duplicates work.

